   136	
   137	Yet no experiment could possibly demonstrate that no cause exists; the
   138	most that one could ever conclude is that no cause was found. But if we
   139	ask, \"Well, how hard did you try to find the cause?\" we will be told:
   140	\"I didn't try at all, because the theory assures us there is none.\"
   141	Then in what sense can one say that any experiments confirm such a
   142	theory? How can anyone feel confident that no causes exist at the
   143	submicroscopic level when experiments give no evidence for this and
   144	experimenters do not search for them? Clearly, such a claim is pure type
   145	(B) Mind Projection Fallacy.
   146	
   147	It is evident that this pattern of thought is also present throughout
   148	orthodox statistics, whenever someone states, or implies, that his
   149	probabilities are real causative agents *en masse* for events that are
   150	not determined, individually, by anything. And we see that there can be
   151	no such thing as a statistical test for \"absence of cause\" or
   152	\"randomness\" or \"disorder\" for the same reason that there is no test
   153	for ugliness or foolishness; those qualities exist only in the eye of
   154	the observer. Now let us see one aspect of this in a specific example.
   155	## Example: The Poisson Distribution {#example-the-poisson-distribution .unnumbered}
